{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604362"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:53:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:53:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15824"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15824"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.18,0.15,0.13,0.33]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71471"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8515"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56980"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8613"},{"type":"tags","id":"8666"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20453"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71471"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, cells from the dorsal neural tube migrate to contribute to heart formation. These neural crest cells are crucial for normal cardiac development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cardiac structures is primarily derived from neural crest cells?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interventricular septum","Aorticopulmonary septum","Heart valves","Cardiac muscle cells","Endocardial cushions"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring cardiac development, neural crest cells migrate from the dorsal neural tube to contribute to several cardiac structures. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eaorticopulmonary septum\u003C/strong\u003E, which separates the outflow tract into the aorta and pulmonary artery, is primarily formed by neural crest cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are derived from other embryological sources:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterventricular septum\u003C/strong\u003E develops from the fusion of muscular and membranous components derived from cardiac mesoderm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeart valves\u003C/strong\u003E form from the endocardial cushions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac muscle cells\u003C/strong\u003E originate from cardiac mesoderm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndocardial cushions\u003C/strong\u003E arise from endocardial cells that undergo epithelial-to-mesenchymal transformation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeural crest cells also give rise to the smooth muscle of the great vessels and cardiac ganglia. Problems with neural crest cell migration can cause congenital heart defects like persistent truncus arteriosus and tetralogy of Fallot.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Neural crest cells migrate from the dorsal neural tube to form key cardiac structures during embryonic development","The aorticopulmonary septum is primarily formed by neural crest cells","Neural crest cells are essential for normal cardiac outflow tract development and their disruption leads to congenital heart defects"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","Kirby ML, Gale TF, Stewart DE. Neural crest cells contribute to normal aorticopulmonary septation. Science. 1983 Jun 3;220(4601):1059-61."]},"relationships":{